.TH TIMEOUT(1),User Commands,TIMEOUT(1)

.SH NAME
timeout - run a command with a time limit

.SH SYNOPSIS
timeout [-fp] [-k time] [-s signal] duration command [arg ...]

.SH DESCRIPTION
The timeout utility runs the given command with the supplied arguments. If the command has not exited after duration seconds, it is killed.

The duration argument is a non-negative integer, optionally followed by a unit suffix:

    s: seconds (default)
    m: minutes
    h: hours
    d: days

timeout exits with the exit status of the command. If the command timed out, timeout exits with status 124.

.SH OPTIONS
-f: Foreground mode. Accepted but has no effect on this platform.

-k time: After the main timeout kills the command, wait time more seconds and send SIGKILL if still running. Accepted but has no effect on this platform.

-p: Preserve the exit status of the command even if it timed out. Accepted but has no effect on this platform.

-s signal: Send signal instead of SIGTERM on timeout. Accepted but has no effect on this platform.

.SH EXIT STATUS
124 if the command timed out, otherwise the exit status of the command.

.SH EXAMPLES
Run a command with a 10 second limit:

$ timeout 10 myprogram

Run with a 2 minute limit:

$ timeout 2m myprogram arg1
